  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jacob’s and Esau’s mother.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—This insertion of particulars already well known is in exact accordance with the Oriental manner of writing, which, moreover, is very careful in impressing all matters of family relation on the mind. (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 25:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) It is worthy of notice that as Jacob has now been confirmed in the possession of the birthright by the father as well as by the mother, his name is placed first.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
